[1] Russia (Chelyabinsk)
Date: Wed 16 Oct 2013
Source: Chelyabinsk.rfn.ru [in Russian, trans., edited]
http://chelyabinsk.rfn.ru/rnews.html?id=870843&cid=7


The 1st cases of measles in 7 years have been recorded in Chelyabinsk. A woman resident of Leninsky district of Chelyabinsk is presently hospitalised. The medical authorities have declared that that there is no need for panic. More than 99 percent of the population in the South Urals region has been vaccinated. However the medical authorities have carried out additional vaccination in the building where the affected patient lives.

According to neighbours the patient is a hospital employee. The medical administration has now confirmed that the initial case was a girl from a family of immigrants with relatives in Kyrgyzstan who came to visit. The sick child was admitted to hospital and passed the infection to the hospital worker. Both patients are being treated and are now recovering.

Svetlana Luchinina, deputy director of the Chelyabinsk region Office of Epidemiology commented that Chelyabinsk is now at risk for a measles outbreak due to the presence of Roma immigrants and that there are 39 cases among this population in Troitsk. Since the incubation period for measles is approximately 3 weeks the residents of the buildings where the Roma families live will remain under surveillance for this period. The occupants are cooperating with the city administration.

[Byline: Dmitry Turkin, Nicholas Makhinya]

