Africa
------
[4] Namibia (Ohangwena)
Date: Fri 18 Oct 2013
Source: The Namibian [edited]
http://www.namibian.com.na/indexx.php?id=4974&page_type=story_detail&category_id=1


The Directorate of Health and Social Services has announced that it is currently busy with a measles vaccination campaign in Ohangwena Region, after another measles outbreak in the Engela district recently.

According to the acting health director for Ohangwena Region, John Hango, 18 measles cases were suspected in September [2013] of which 5 have been confirmed.

Hango said the ministry started the vaccination campaign on Tuesday [15 Oct 2013] in villages where the cases were confirmed, as well as in other 12 surrounding villages. These include Oshikango, Onamhinda, Eeshoke, Ohalushu, Okamukwa, and Omafo. All children between 6 months and 5 years in those areas will have to be vaccinated, Hango announced.

Hango also told The Namibian that so far the ministry has managed to vaccinate close to 3000 children, with most of them coming from the Oshikango area. The Acting Health Director said they were suspecting the measles to have come from southern Angola. "Namibia's regions bordering with other countries, such as Angola, are always in a crisis when these kind of diseases are reported in those countries. We always have to be on the outlook and put measures in place, such as the diagnosing of those diseases among our people, to treat and immunise the suspect villagers," Hango said and added that the vaccination campaign that will end today [18 Oct 2013] has been going very well. He explained that the vaccination teams worked very hard and tried to get through to all target groups in the affected villages.

"We have everything in place, and will fight this measles disease in our region," Hango stated, commenting that this disease had made its appearance at the same time last year and that then too, it was successfully controlled.

[Byline: Oswald Shivute]

