[6] Australia (New South Wales)
Date: Fri 18 Oct 2013
Source: The Daily Telegraph [edited]
http://www.dailytelegraph.com.au/news/nsw/fears-of-measles-outbreak-in-byron-as-mother-and-son-attend-hospital/story-fni0cx12-1226742479245


There are fears of a serious measles outbreak around Byron Bay after a 7-year-old boy and his mother attended hospital yesterday [17 Oct 2013] with the highly contagious disease. It is understood the boy was not vaccinated and his mother was a registered conscientious objector. Their case comes after a 13-year-old Byron Bay boy was diagnosed with measles last week, sparking a major health warning after it was revealed he had visited Dreamworld, on the Gold Coast, earlier this month [October 2013]. And yesterday [17 Oct 2013] it was revealed another teenager had been diagnosed with measles after attending Byron Bay High School from Monday to Wednesday, and catching the Bangalow-Byron bus each day. 3 other people in the Byron Bay area have been diagnosed with measles over the past 2 weeks the unit said in a statement today [18 Oct 2013].

The North Coast Public Health Unit has advised people in the area to be alert for measles and will run a free vaccination clinic at Byron High [School] on Monday [21 Oct 2013]. Byron Shire has the lowest rates of immunisation in the state -- just 46 per cent of 2-year-olds in Mullumbimby and 69 percent in Byron, well below the state average of 92 per cent.

A North Coast resident, whose 7-year-old daughter died of the measles complication subacute sclerosing panencephalitis (SSPE), said it was outrageous other children were being put at risk. "You only get SSPE through measles and these kids could be a time bomb, no child survives SSPE," her mother said. [But that mother had presumably failed to get her own daughter vaccinated. SSPE strikes about 1/100 000 measles cases, and may take several years post-infection to appear. - Mod.JW]

According to the latest National Communicable Diseases Surveillance Report for the fortnight 21 Sep to 4 Oct 2013, there have been 69 cases of measles reported so far this year [2013]. The median age of all cases this year is 21 years and based on vaccination status data, over 50 per cent, or 34 of the total cases this year were not vaccinated, "including 2 infants who were less than one year of age and too young for vaccination," the report said. 12 of the cases (17 per cent) were vaccinated, but all but one had only had one dose, not the recommended 2 doses of the MMR vaccine. The remaining 22 cases were of unknown vaccination status.

[Byline: Jane Hansen]

--
