[7] Australia (Queensland)
Date: Mon 14 Oct 2013
Source: The Australian [edited]
http://www.theaustralian.com.au/news/vaccination-noshows-prompt-toplevel-measles-outbreak-warning/story-e6frg6n6-1226739273248


[Queensland's] top doctor has taken the extraordinary step of writing to the parents of more than 13 000 children to ram home the warnings about the state's measles outbreak. With help from the Australian Childhood Immunisation Register, Queensland Chief Health Officer Jeannette Young has identified 13 117 Queensland children aged between 4 and 6 who have missed scheduled vaccinations, and written to their families to urge them to immunise their children.

Since August [2013], 16 people have contracted measles in southeast Queensland. Most of those diagnosed have been from Ipswich, west of Brisbane. Dr Young said most areas of Queensland had 90 per cent of children fully vaccinated, with the Torres Strait and Cape York regions having the highest rates of immunisation. The Gold Coast and Sunshine Coast regions are below national rates, with more than one in 10 children either not immunised at all, or missing some of their scheduled vaccinations.

Dr Young said this was the 1st time she had used the Australian Childhood Immunisation Registry to approach parents and urge them to vaccinate their children. She said she would continue to work with registry staff to identify Queensland children younger than 4 who were not adequately vaccinated, and planned to write to contact their families as well.

Dr Young said measles was a very serious disease which could have potentially life-threatening consequences. Some patients with the virus develop pneumonia and encephalitis, or inflammation of the brain. "Around one-third of adults who contract it require hospitalisation," she said.

[Byline: Janelle Miles)

